<subSubSection id="39CBB18F9023640CFF3C84BEFE9BB166" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="716EE2049023640CFF3C84BEFE9BB166" blockId="4.[192,1440,706,793]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="43A53E169023640CFF3C84BEFEC3B0A5" bold="true" box="[192,348,706,730]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species epithet, 
<taxonomicName id="B6D199879023640CFDA684BEFD20B0A6" authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="2015" box="[602,703,706,729]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Paraberismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imitator">
<emphasis id="43A53E169023640CFDA684BEFD20B0A6" box="[602,703,706,729]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">imitator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a noun in apposition referring to the fact that this species has the general appearance of a species of 
<taxonomicName id="B6D199879023640CFD3D849EFCA1B086" box="[705,830,738,761]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Berismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="43A53E169023640CFD3D849EFCA1B086" box="[705,830,738,761]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Berismyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
rather than the other known species of 
<taxonomicName id="B6D199879023640CFADC849EFF62B166" authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="1995" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Paraberismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="43A53E169023640CFADC849EFF62B166" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Paraberismyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="39CBB18F9023640CFF3C853EFC50B6E5" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="716EE2049023640CFF3C853EFC50B6E5" blockId="4.[192,1441,834,1178]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="43A53E169023640CFF3C853EFEDCB125" bold="true" box="[192,323,834,858]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="B6D199879023640CFEB4853EFDFBB126" authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="2015" box="[328,612,834,858]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Paraberismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imitator">
<emphasis id="43A53E169023640CFEB4853EFDFBB126" box="[328,612,834,858]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Paraberismyia imitator</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is yet another species of the genus found in the highlands of Chiapas. Remarkably, all known specimens of the genus were collected at only three localities. All four species treated by 
<bibRefCitation id="15409FF59023640CFEC385FEFE69B1E5" author="Woodley, N. E." box="[319,502,898,922]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="25 - 45" refId="ref2960" refString="Woodley, N. E. 2013. A revision of the Neotropical genus Paraberismyia Woodley (Diptera, Stratiomyidae, Beridinae) with three new species. ZooKeys 353: 25 - 45." type="journal article" year="2013">Woodley (2013)</bibRefCitation>
were collected at El Triunfo, Chiapas, in May, 1985. This site is at the southern end of the Sierra Madre de Chiapas. One of these, 
<taxonomicName id="B6D199879023640CFCD485DEFBCEB1C5" authority="Woodley" authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="1995" box="[808,1105,930,954]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Paraberismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tzontehuitza">
<emphasis id="43A53E169023640CFCD485DEFC40B1C5" box="[808,991,930,954]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">P. tzontehuitza</emphasis>
Woodley
</taxonomicName>
, had been described earlier (
<bibRefCitation id="15409FF59023640CFF3485BEFE30B1A6" author="Woodley, N. E." box="[200,431,961,986]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 231" refId="ref2929" refString="Woodley, N. E. 1995. The genera of Beridinae (Diptera: Stratiomyidae). Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Washington 16: 1 - 231." type="journal article" year="1995">Woodley 1995: 136</bibRefCitation>
) from Cerro Tzontehuitz, Chiapas, which is in the Central Highlands. The species described herein is from the same locality. Old specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="B6D199879023640CFC49859EFB57B185" authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="2013" box="[949,1224,994,1018]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Paraberismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triunfo">
<emphasis id="43A53E169023640CFC49859EFB57B185" box="[949,1224,994,1018]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Paraberismyia triunfo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected in 
<collectingRegion id="B3152CE69023640CFF3C827EFEC3B665" box="[192,348,1026,1050]" country="Guatemala" name="Totonicapan" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Totonicapán</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="09C6A2949023640CFE94827EFE6BB665" box="[360,500,1026,1050]" name="Guatemala" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
, which is in the Sierra Madre that is essentially a southern extension of the Sierra Madre de Chiapas. Given the relatively little amount of collecting that has been done in this region and the number of species already known from this area, it seems very likely that still more species of 
<taxonomicName id="B6D199879023640CFEC7821EFE6FB605" authorityName="Woodley" authorityYear="1995" box="[315,496,1122,1146]" class="Insecta" family="Stratiomyidae" genus="Paraberismyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="43A53E169023640CFEC7821EFE6FB605" box="[315,496,1122,1146]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Paraberismyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will be discovered. It also indicates that the highland regions of Chiapas and adjacent 
<collectingCountry id="09C6A2949023640CFECC82FEFE26B6E5" box="[304,441,1154,1178]" name="Guatemala" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
are biodiverse and rich in endemic species.
</paragraph>
